# Prometheus HTTP API v1 — Status Endpoints & Feature Reporting

All code lives in **`/app/web/api/v1/api.go`** unless noted.

## 1. Status endpoint registration

In `func (api *API) Register(r *route.Router)` (starts at **line 392**), the status endpoints are registered at **lines 456–463**:

```go
456	r.Get("/status/config", wrap(api.serveConfig))
457	r.Get("/status/runtimeinfo", wrap(api.serveRuntimeInfo))
458	r.Get("/status/buildinfo", wrap(api.serveBuildInfo))
459	r.Get("/status/flags", wrap(api.serveFlags))
460	r.Get("/status/tsdb", wrapAgent(api.serveTSDBStatus))
461	r.Get("/status/tsdb/blocks", wrapAgent(api.serveTSDBBlocks))
462	r.Get("/features", wrap(api.features))
463	r.Get("/status/walreplay", api.serveWALReplayStatus)
```

Note the two registration styles:
- `wrap(...)` / `wrapAgent(...)` take an `apiFunc` and return an `http.HandlerFunc` (the common pattern; `wrapAgent` returns an error if running in agent mode).
- `/status/walreplay` is registered with a raw `http.HandlerFunc` (`serveWALReplayStatus` writes to the `ResponseWriter` directly), not via `wrap`.

For your new `GET /api/v1/status/reload`, the idiomatic choice is `r.Get("/status/reload", wrap(api.serveReloadStatus))`.

### The wrap/apiFunc pattern (lines 198–205, 393–423)

```go
198	type apiFuncResult struct {
199		data      any
200		err       *apiError
201		warnings  annotations.Annotations
202		finalizer func()
203	}
204	
205	type apiFunc func(r *http.Request) apiFuncResult
```

`wrap` (lines 393–414) sets CORS, calls the `apiFunc`, and then: on `result.err` calls `api.respondError`; on non-nil `result.data` calls `api.respond`; otherwise writes `204 No Content`. It also wraps everything in `api.ready(...)`, compression, and the OpenAPI handler.

